Certainly! I'll add log statements to help with checking and debugging. Here's the modified code with log statements inserted:

```java
public boolean deleteFileModel(final FileModel fileModel) {
    Log.d("DeleteFileModel", "Starting deletion of: " + fileModel.getPath());
    Stack<FileModel> stack = new Stack<>();
    stack.push(fileModel);

    boolean success = true;

    while (!stack.isEmpty()) {
        if (isCancelled()) {
            Log.d("DeleteFileModel", "Operation cancelled");
            return false;
        }

        FileModel currentFile = stack.peek();  // Peek instead of pop
        Log.d("DeleteFileModel", "Processing: " + currentFile.getPath());

        if (currentFile.isDirectory()) {
            FileModel[] list = currentFile.list();
            if (list == null || list.length == 0) {
                // Directory is empty or can't be read, try to delete it
                stack.pop();
                Log.d("DeleteFileModel", "Attempting to delete empty directory: " + currentFile.getPath());
                boolean deleteResult = deleteFile(currentFile);
                success &= deleteResult;
                Log.d("DeleteFileModel", "Delete result for " + currentFile.getPath() + ": " + deleteResult);
            } else {
                // Add children to the stack
                Log.d("DeleteFileModel", "Adding " + list.length + " children to stack for: " + currentFile.getPath());
                for (FileModel child : list) {
                    stack.push(child);
                }
            }
        } else {
            // It's a file, pop and delete it
            stack.pop();
            Log.d("DeleteFileModel", "Attempting to delete file: " + currentFile.getPath());
            boolean deleteResult = deleteFile(currentFile);
            success &= deleteResult;
            Log.d("DeleteFileModel", "Delete result for " + currentFile.getPath() + ": " + deleteResult);
        }
    }

    Log.d("DeleteFileModel", "Deletion process completed. Overall success: " + success);
    return success;
}
```

These log statements will help you track the progress of the deletion process, including:
- When the deletion starts and for which file/directory
- When the operation is cancelled
- Which file or directory is being processed at each step
- The result of each deletion attempt
- How many children are being added to the stack for each directory
- The overall success of the operation

